# AI Economic Impact - Project Overview

## What this repo is
A research initiative studying the **economic impact of AI** (impact on jobs, working hours, sectors, wages, productivity, and more), grounded in applied microeconomics: causal inference, organizational and behavioural economics.

This repo acts as a **second brain and research assistant**: it ingests papers, datasets, and theoretical models, and turns them into structured notes, analyses, and simulations.

## Repo structure
- `papers/` - raw PDFs (input only)
- `notes/papers/` - one Markdown note per paper (research questions, methodology, results)
- `notes/concepts/` - thematic notes on AI economic impact (jobs, working hours, sectors, wages, productivity, etc.)
- `data/` - datasets
- `notebooks/` - exploratory data analysis
- `simulations/` - simulations using data + theoretical models from papers
- `src/` - shared, reusable Python code

## Tooling baseline
- **Environment & dependencies**: `uv` (use `uv add`, `uv run`)
- **Lint + format**: `Ruff` (`ruff check .`, `ruff format .`)
- **Type checking**: `mypy`
- **Core libraries**: pandas, numpy; matplotlib/plotly for viz; PyMC for Bayesian work

## Conventions
- Type-hint function signatures; keep functions small and testable.
- Put reusable logic in `src/`; import it into notebooks rather than copy-pasting.
- Keep all written knowledge (paper summaries, concepts) as Markdown.
- Prefer reproducibility: seed randomness, make notebooks runnable top-to-bottom.

## Living document
These rules are a starting point. Keep them **short** and update them as the project evolves and best practices emerge - edit the relevant rule in `.cursor/rules/`, and keep `README.md` in sync when structure or setup changes.

## Working notes
Session history and decision records live in `.cursor/notes/` (see the `session-logging` rule). Read `.cursor/notes/session-log.md` at the start of a session.
